<br>
1) Jolt has roughly the same failure rate as Evade when all the factors are added in.<br>
2) Jolt drops 500 from the ranger hate total.<br>
3) Evade will drop 500 or XX% whichever is greater.<br>
4) A &quot;normal&quot; melee class dual weilding and double attacking generates 280 hate per combat round (roughly 70 point damage X4).<br>
5) Dual wielding or double attacking alone also generate 280 hate per combat round (140 points damage x2)<br>
<br>
On these assumptions, all melee classes generate hate at the same rate without using spells, special attacks, or procs.  So they also generate hate at the same rate if they hit at about the same percentage.  The hit miss ratio is mitigated by the fact that missed attacks generate some hate, but not as much as a full hit (my assumption, probably not fact).<br>
<br>
So a rogue fighting, backstabbing, and evading needs to match (or be slightly below) a warrior taunting, kicking, critical hitting, and bashing or a ranger fighting, casting, taunting, etc. to keep things balanced.  Or one would think that is the goal.<br>
<br>
However the concern I have is that the rates at which these &quot;special&quot; attacks or avoidances can be done will unbalance the equation.  A rogue with haste gets a 6 sec refresh on backstab (if I recall correctly) and can get that down to roughly 4 secs with RB and Shissar type haste.  Post 55 nearly double that rate with double backstab.  Evade is a 10 sec clock.  Rangers get spells roughly every (totally guessing) 8 secs, haste has no effect, and they can Jolt every 1.5 secs.  In essence they generate hate slower and avoid hate faster.  Also warrior critical hits come slower and do less damage than backstabs, so their &quot;generate hate&quot; factor is relatively slow without taunt.  Taunt is 8 secs, not effected by haste? (never played warrior, not sure on numbers)<br>
<br>
So if the rogue's &quot;generate hate&quot; factor is roughly 3 times that of another melee class, then evade needs to have roughly 3 times the effectiveness, either in frequency of use, or scale of impact on hate list rankings, to keep things relatively balanced.  Obviously failed evades, misses, or other reasonably random factors will change that in reality, but the theoretical balance will be there.  Give the slight edge to rogues and you have a class that can stay effective while still being subject to all the same combat factors they are now, but they will be close to the list top because they generate hate so quickly.<br>
<br>
Solutions:<br>
1)  Increase frequency of use on a lower effective Evade or make Evade more effective per use with a longer attempt time.  Maybe let evade refresh faster on a failure but leave a longer timer on a successful evade?<br>
2)  Ensure that at 55th level Evade's effectiveness can also be increased.  If you give everyone evade that works for post 55 rogues then it will be too effective at 54-, or if post 55 we get an evade that works well at lower levels we'll be way under equipped to deal with a double backstab hate generation.<br>
3)  Possibly allow Evade to move the rogue from 2-3 position to 5 position depending on success roll. <p><A HREF=mailto:jordinn@aquilo.org><B>Jordinn Spiritstalker</B></A><BR>
<B><A HREF=Http://www.aquilo.org>Aquilo Phoenix</A></B><BR>
<I>55th Level Blackguard, Povar</I><BR>
