"click...creaaak"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ul0z.showPublicProfile?language=EN>L0z</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.geocities.com/lozdarogue/Rbsmall.JPG BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/8/01 10:13:45 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/lozdarogue/Ragebringer.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Zen and the Art of Evade Mechanics</span><hr size=1> 500 points ain't jack. neither would 1500 points be keen either.  Here, lemme write some psudo code for you =P<br>
<br>
Given that:<br>
rogue_hate = integer value representation of the amount of hate that the rogue has<br>
Other_hate[x] = integer value representation of the amount of hate that others have, with x representing their order on the hate list (1 highest, 120 lowest)<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------<br>
function random_hate (rogue_hate);<br>
rogue hate becomes equal to (rogue_hate - random[1000 to 3000]);<br>
<br>
function evade (int rogue_hate, other_hate[x]);<br>
if evade = true<br>
   if rogue_hate > other_hate<br>
      then rogue_hate becomes equal to ((other_hate[10])-100)<br>
   else<br>
      then rogue_hate becomes equal to (rogue_hate - (random_hate[rogue_hate]))<br>
else<br>
   rogue_hate stays the same<br>
----------------------------------------<br>
<br>
What am I getting at?  Well, assuming that I didn't f00kup, which is a big assumption, and we all know assumption is the mother of all f_ups, we have what I think the evade skill should do.<br>
<br>
<b>How is this different from what is going on now(currently, before changes)?</b><br>
Currently, what you would see is (if evade = true, then rogue_hate := 120), essentially putting the rogue at the bottom of the hate list.<br>
<br>
<b>How is this different from the current proposal?</b><br>
What this does is move the rogue 100 points under the 10th person on the hate list.  What I forgot to do was put in a min hate cap that you can evade to, which should be ~500-1000.<br>
<br>
<b>Why do you think you're right, and Kendrick's not?</b><br>
Simple.  I play.  Every night.  7 nights a week, 6 hours+ a day.  In raids.  In xp groups (even though I'm 60, i still resort to getting xp).  In essence, I probably play this game longer than people at verant work.  I know my friend in QA is an exception to this rule, as during his QA testing of Velious, he was at work 12-13 hours a day.  And then he'd come home and play EQ.  /cheer.  What I'm getting at is that while I'm not putting myself above Kendrick's knowledge, What I am doing is saying that I like to think i have a pretty good idea of what I'm talking about.  I don't think Kendrick's <i>wrong</i>, except for maybe the part where he thinks this won't affect us too much...  but he knows that's not the case too.<br>
<br>
<b>Why so much hate reduction?</b><br>
Well, a couple people have brought up Jolt as an example, including Kendrick himself.  Let me tell you a few things about jolt.  <br>
Casting time: 1.5 seconds.  <br>
Spell recovery: 2.0 seconds.  <br>
effect: removes 500 points of hate from the target's hate list<br>
So, what Kendrick is saying is that Evade should only be *slightly* better than Jolt, yet you can continue to cast Jolt, getting ~3 casts in in the 10 seconds that it takes evade to recycle... which means, for every 500 points of reduction that a rogue gets, rangers can get 1500.  That in itself is significant, but it's not the most heinous part.  Rangers aren't supposed to do more damage than rogues... yet they can get more hate reduction than us... Think there's something wrong there? I agree with you.<br>
<br>
<b>Wow! You've convinced me!  Rogues really *will* get shafted on this one.</b><br>
Good, i'm glad I've made my point.<br>
